[Student "S"]
{Partner's 3\D bid shows a 5-card suit and is forcing to game. While 5\D is possibly the best contract your double \H stopper should sway you to 3NT instead. This is the old "9 tricks are easier than 11" principle.

North plays 3NT. As expected, East attacks in his \H suit.

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 2 : \D = 0 : \C = 2 :: Total = 6

Even if West holds both black Queens, (not likely), you can only finesse your way to 8 tricks. Since you need 9 tricks you must establish the \D suit.

If East holds both the \DA and \DK then you are going down, because they will win the race to establish \Hs before you can establish \Ds. 

But when the \DA and \DK are in different hands you have a good chance for success; it depends on West having no \H at the time he takes his \D winner. 

So you should hold up on the first \H trick and win the second. If East started with 6 \Hs then West will be out. So whether he wins his \D trick first or second he still won't be able to continue \Hs.

After your hold up West has no \Hs. If he takes the first \D trick he will have to lead another suit. You will still have a \H stopper for when East wins <b>HIS</b> \D trick.

On the other hand, if East takes the first \D trick he can certainly drive out your last \H stopper. But then, when West takes <b>HIS</b> \D winner he will have no \H.

Finally, if East had only a 5-card \H suit, good defense would beat you. But they have to be sure West wins the first \D trick, and they might slip up. }
[Play "W"]HQ

