{Partner's 2NT opening shows 20-21 points so you know you want to be in game. To find out which game you bid a Stayman 3\C. Partner replies 3\D.  

Partner's 2NT opening shows 20-21 points so you know you want to be in game. To find out which game you bid a Stayman 3\C. Partner replies 3\D. 

You don't have a 4-4 \H fit, so you bid 3NT.

The contract would be 3NT played by West.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \S3. Your first problem is which \S to play from dummy. That is an easy problem. If you play the \SK you might lose the first five or six tricks. If you play low you guarantee a \S stopper. North plays the \SA and returns the \S7 to dummy's \SK. South plays the \S2 on this trick.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 1 : \D = 3 : \C = 2 :: Total = 7

You need 2 more winners, and you need to get them before you lose the lead because it appears that South can cash 3 more \S tricks.

That means you need all 5 \D tricks. The good news is that the 5 missing \Ds will split 3-2 about two-thirds of the time. The bad news is that they will be 4-1 about one-third of the time. Can you protect yourself against a 4-1 break? 

Maybe and maybe not. If South has \D J x x x there won't be anything you can do about it. But if North has this holding then you can succeed if you play your cards right. 

<i>Did you like that "play your cards right" quip?</i>First play a \D to your \DK; both defenders follow. Next play a \D to dummy's \DQ. South discards a \C. You are conveniently in dummy so you play dummy's last \D and North's \D J 9 are caught in a pincer movement by your \D A 10 5. 

It was important to play the \Ds exactly as described because dummy had only one entry left, the \DQ.

Suppose your first \D play had been dummy's \DQ. You could make your contract if you play a small \D and finesse the \D10. But at that point you wouldn't know whether the \Ds were splitting evenly or not. You'd be risking defeat on a hand where everybody who played for the 3-2 split was making the contract.

By taking the <b>SECOND</b> \D trick with dummy's \DQ the 4-1 split is exposed at the right time.}
[Play "W"]S3

